channel.name: Questions about protokit and o1js frontend integration

messages.content:
Hi! While developing a mina game we have some questions. 
1. Mina UI integration suggests to compile circuit in service worker (https://docs.minaprotocol.com/zkapps/tutorials/zkapp-ui-with-react#create-an-instance). Compilation is a quite heavy operation. Is it possible to compile the circuit in advance by us and put to frontend the compilation result? If not, why?

2. Protokit doesn't deal with addresses. Contract is resolved like ```const balances = client.runtime.resolve("Balances");``` (https://github.com/proto-kit/starter-kit/blob/develop/apps/web/lib/stores/balances.tsx#L49)
 What is the address of the balances contract, how can it be found on the live network? 

3. Can protokit be connected to a not local testnet like Berkeley? Is it planned to support not only the local network? If yes, when?

4. We need to deploy game competition smartcontract instances for different competitions. Is it possible to deploy a smartcontract using protokit? 

5. Having a private address for a smartcontract seems quite unusual. What ability does the owner of the contact's private key have? If we deploy competitions from frontend, how to deal with the private key?

6. Is there a protokit way of frontend proof generation or the only way is to create a o1js ZkProgram and create proof in worker?

1. You can try @0xKriss1897  [solution](https://discord.com/channels/484437221055922177/1171938451193593856/1172278215637733407) for caching pre-compiled prover keys on Web. More info on it:
https://discord.com/channels/484437221055922177/915745847692636181/1175384263248584795

Hi @asimaranov | xRaise x ZkNoid, thanks for your questions. I think the first one already got answered by DFST 👍 
2. In protokit, we don't have the concept of addresses by default for contracts (which we call runtime modules). Instead, all of your code will be aggregated into multiple zk-circuits that are then merged, produce a single proof including all of the execution you did, and are then submitted to the Mina chain to be included and finalize the state (we call that "settlement"). All you runtime modules can interoperate with each other, but since there is currently no way to dynamically add runtime code (as traditional smartcontract allow you - we will add that fairly soon though), there is no need for addresses, since you can identify modules by their name.

3. Currently, we only support running protokit locally, but the only thing that is missing from enabling operation on berkeley is us writing the settlement contracts. We want to complete that until the end of next week though, so if you start building with protokit now, by the time you are finished, you will be able to deploy it on berkeley 🙂

4. As previously said, protokit doesn't have "smart contracts" yet. But it should be no problem to emulate smart contracts by just storing values inside a "StateMap" and distinguishing games that way. If you need help to design the system, we are happy to help!

5. afaik, PrivateKeys for smartcontracts are only used for deploying the verificationkey at the time of contract creation. You should always set the permissions of your contract to Permission.Proof, so that the state and balance can only be modified by submitting a valid proof and you privatekey becomes useless

6. Yes! You can use o1js ZkPrograms by default with protokit and consume client-side produced proofs inside protokit runtimes. That means that you can prove your privacy-sensitive stuff on the user's machine, and then handle the on-chain stuff inside of protokit.
Thanks for the answer. But it seems `compile` function has no argument `cache` for now and there're no type `Cache` in o1js
You are probably using an old o1js version. Cache is working starting from o1js 0.14.2
Seems that protokit is hardly bound to the o1js 0.13.1...
It is, but we'll upgrade it again in the coming weeks. You can start developing with Protokit today, its advisable to use mock proofs during development & testing as well
unfortunately until o1js enters a stable release and starts following semver, we're playing cat and mouse catching up with the versions
We're building zknoid.io and we just came to the stage where we want to generate the proof on frontend
Are all of your features complete with mock proofs?
Got something else to do. Will try to implement custom competitions creation using StateMaps and wait for the protokit update. Or maybe will try to support contracts for both protokit and mina
That sounds like a good idea, i think you should focus on developing more features such as leaderboards, making use of the state maps
